{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523817"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:58:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:58:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13922"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13922"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.83,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111229"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1406"},{"type":"tags","id":"6549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13102"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111229"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-week history of a painless ulcer on the sole of his left foot. He noticed it while washing his feet but cannot recall any injury. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 10 years ago, hypertension, and hyperlipidaemia. His medications include metformin, gliclazide, perindopril, and atorvastatin. He works as an office manager and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Inspection of his left foot reveals a 2 cm diameter ulcer on the plantar surface of the second metatarsal head. The ulcer has a clean base with granulation tissue and no purulent discharge (Image). There is callus formation around the edges of the ulcer. Monofilament testing shows reduced sensation in both feet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent surgical debridement","Empirical oral antibiotics","Pressure offloading with appropriate footwear","Referral for endocrinology review","Daily saline dressings"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENeuropathic foot ulcers in people with diabetes are primarily caused by loss of protective sensation and abnormal pressure distribution, often at weight-bearing sites. The most important initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003Epressure offloading with appropriate footwear\u003C/strong\u003E, such as a removable cast walker or custom orthotic device. This reduces mechanical trauma, prevents further tissue damage, and promotes healing by addressing the underlying biomechanical cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical debridement\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if there is necrotic tissue, deep infection, or evidence of osteomyelitis. In this case, the ulcer has a clean base with granulation tissue and no signs of infection or necrosis, so debridement is not required at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpirical oral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are reserved for ulcers with clinical evidence of infection, such as purulent discharge, surrounding erythema, or systemic symptoms. This ulcer is not infected, so antibiotics are not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for endocrinology review\u003C/strong\u003E may be important for optimising glycaemic control, which is essential for wound healing and long-term management. Involving endocrinology is ideal in challenging or refractory cases, but it is not the immediate management step to promote healing of the current ulcer. The priority is to address the mechanical cause through offloading.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily saline dressings\u003C/strong\u003E may be used as part of local wound care, but without pressure offloading, dressings alone are unlikely to result in healing. Offloading is the key intervention to address the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Offloading pressure is the cornerstone of management for neuropathic diabetic foot ulcers.","Early involvement of a multidisciplinary team improves outcomes in diabetic foot ulcer care.","Optimising glycaemic control and regular wound assessment are essential in promoting healing in patients with diabetic foot ulcers."],"references":["Reardon R. RACGP - Diabetic foot ulcer [Internet]. 2020. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2020/may/diabetic-foot-ulcer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93359"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13922"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20855"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20855"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SF8zLoCBReajVKsshingcXoeeCPphP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SF8zLoCBReajVKsshingcXoeeCPphP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93359"},"attributes":{"create